You can share an OpenAPI/Swagger contract in two ways.

Since your app is on Spring Boot 4, first check whether your project already has a Swagger/OpenAPI dependency. If it does, start Arthur Core and try:

```text
https://arthur-core.kubernetes.localhost/arthur-core/v3/api-docs
```

That returns the generated OpenAPI JSON file. You can download/save that JSON and share it with the B2Boost team.

For a browser UI, try:

```text
https://arthur-core.kubernetes.localhost/arthur-core/swagger-ui/index.html
```

Some newer Springdoc setups also expose Scalar instead of Swagger UI:

```text
https://arthur-core.kubernetes.localhost/arthur-core/scalar
```

Springdoc generates the OpenAPI description at `/v3/api-docs` from your controllers and DTOs. ([OpenAPI 3 Library for spring-boot][1])

For B2Boost, the important endpoint is:

```text
POST /arthur-core/auth/handoff/exchange
```

with request:

```json
{
  "code": "one-time-handoff-code"
}
```

and response based on your `HandoffExchangeResponse`.

Because you are using Spring Boot 4, be careful before adding an older `springdoc-openapi` dependency. Springdoc 2.x is documented for Spring Boot 3, while Springdoc 3.x added Boot 4 / Jackson 3 support. ([OpenAPI 3 Library for spring-boot][2])

The cleanest immediate approach is:

1. Add OpenAPI annotations to `exchange(...)` and the request/response DTOs.
2. Generate `/v3/api-docs`.
3. Download the JSON.
4. Share that JSON file with B2Boost.

For example:

```java
@Operation(
        summary = "Exchange a one-time Arthur handoff code",
        description = """
                Called server-to-server by B2Boost after browser redirection.
                The handoff code is short-lived and can be used only once.
                """
)
@ApiResponses({
        @ApiResponse(
                responseCode = "200",
                description = "Handoff exchanged successfully"
        ),
        @ApiResponse(
                responseCode = "400",
                description = "Invalid, expired, or already-used handoff code"
        )
})
@PostMapping("/handoff/exchange")
public ResponseEntity<HandoffExchangeResponse> exchange(
        @RequestBody HandoffExchangeRequest request) {

    return ResponseEntity.ok(
            handoffService.exchange(request.getCode()));
}
```

And document the request DTO:

```java
@Data
public class HandoffExchangeRequest {

    @Schema(
            description = "Short-lived one-time code received in the B2Boost redirect URL",
            example = "8a54e13c-7341-4cbd-a87a-2b6ec8d4e021",
            requiredMode = Schema.RequiredMode.REQUIRED
    )
    private String code;
}
```

Then B2Boost gets a proper machine-readable Swagger file instead of screenshots or manually maintained Word documentation.

